Note
Increase from fiscal year (FY) 2026 to FY 2027 provides for accelerated development of advanced capabilities, demonstrations, and prototypes to counter rapidly
evolving threats by utilizing investments in disruptive technologies in the areas of advanced sensing, low-cost interceptors, propulsion and kill vehicles, and a National
Integrated Air and Missile Defense Center that will unify the entire Missile Defense enterprise. Primary increase due to acceleration of the NIC and low-cost interceptor
acceleration initiatives. Additional changes include consolidation of the requirements from Program Element (PE) 0603176C Advanced Concepts and Performance
Assessment requirements into PE 0603180C.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The threat is evolving and becoming more complex, which introduces new challenges for missile defense. Some of these complex challenges include the volume
of threats, system performance in raids, latency across the kill chain, communication between disparate systems, performance in a contested environment and
cybersecurity of networks/systems. These challenges to missile defense require more disruptive capabilities like the following:

- Kinetic & hypersonic defense in the areas of advanced sensing and low-cost systems.
- Non-kinetics and electronic warfare.
- Next generation command, control & integration.
- Disruptive technology and space demonstrations.
- National Integrated Air and Missile Defense Center.
- Cyber Protection / Information Assurance.

The Cyber Operations project supports both the security and effective execution of program office mission-related activities to include information assurance and cyber
network defense.

Program Wide Support contains non-headquarter management costs and activities in support of the Missile Defense Agency (MDA) functions across the entire Missile
Defense System.


