Congressional Add: Advanced Energetics for Deeply Buried Targets ($4.0 million)
- Conduct study and laboratory demonstration to determine optimum material and design for small packing size.
FY 2027 Plans:
Planned efforts in support of advancing disruptive capabilities to include, but not limited to:

National Integrated Air and Missile Defense (IAMD) Center (NIC):
- Distribute integrated multi-domain, multi-service live, virtual and constructive system into a hybrid physical and virtual platform
using a phased approach to field NIC initial operational nodes for IAMD capability with an agile growth plan for improved
capabilities, connectivity, automation, facilities/infrastructure, and capacity. The center will provide a competitive advantage
by enhancing decision making, advanced data analytics, intuitive visualization, joint training and experimentation/concept of
operations development, M&S rapid prototyping, and seamless integration and Warfighter collaboration.
- Deploy NIC nodes for participation in geographically dispersed live demonstrations, wargames, and ground/flight tests.
- Provide independent government performance evaluations, prototyping emerging technologies, including simulated exercises,
across evolving kinetic and non-kinetic concepts for regional and homeland defense.

Low-Cost Interceptor (LCI):
- The multi-year program plan is for rapid design, testing, demonstration, and confirm manufacturability and high rate producibility
for a low cost, hypersonic missile interceptor. In FY27, efforts include detailed design from multiple vendors and initial fire control
system integration.

Low-Cost Kill Vehicle:
- Initiate development and test components that are significantly lower cost and producible in large quantities with little to no
reduction in performance and reliability
- Invest in low-cost divert and attitude control systems, seekers, kill effectors, guidance navigation and control, and cooperative
engagement algorithms.

Low-Cost Kill Booster:
- Initiate design and development of advanced boosters to reduce costs and incorporate new technologies that enable higher
booster performance. Program will focus on technology that is scalable for high throughput production.

Project Maverick:

