Note
Increase from Fiscal Year (FY) 2026 to FY 2027 provides funding for:
- Advanced hardware and software design development for Ground-Based Midcourse Defense (GMD) Fire Control (GFC), Ground Support Systems (GSS), and Phased
Array Flight Interceptor Communications Systems Data Terminal (IDT) to enable mixed-fleet operations with both Ground Based Interceptors and Next Generation
Interceptors.
- Increased lab hardware required for modeling, simulation, integration testing, discrimination support, and lab infrastructure for mixed fleet testing.
- Initiate hardware updates to implement new Department of War compliance directives, enhancing network cybersecurity protections.
- Initiation development of upgrades to the Cyber Security Manager (CSM) and GMD Communication Network (GCN) to mitigate obsolescence and improve cyber
defense and compliance with NIST 800.53.
- Increase for Model Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) to create initial Ground Systems (GS) models.
- Initiation of operational capabilities of the Fort Greely, Alaska, Communications Center (FGACC) providing diverse communications at the Missile Defense Complex.

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Ballistic Missile Defense Midcourse Defense Segment enables the GMD Weapon System (GWS) to provide the combatant commands, including United States
Northern Command (USNORTHCOM), with a continuously available (24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year) Homeland Defense Weapon System. The
GWS contributes to the Missile Defense System by acquiring, developing, demonstrating, deploying, and sustaining an operational Weapon System with Ground
Based Interceptors, development of a GWS with a mixed fleet of Ground Based Interceptors and Next Generation Interceptors, improved Warfighter capabilities, and
Interceptor Fleet Management. The GWS leverages integration of Missile Defense sensors from across the globe to enable the interceptors to deliver kill vehicles to
counter allocated threats in space during the midcourse phase of the threat's ballistic trajectory.

 The Ground Systems consist of the GFC, GCN / GWS Network Infrastructure (GNI), IDT, and GSS. The GFC consists of two (2) GFC nodes at Fort Greely, Alaska
 (FGA) and at the Missile Defense Integration and Operations Center in Colorado Springs, Colorado. The GFC plans midcourse engagements and provides the human-
 in-control interface to the Warfighter. As a critical component of Ground Systems, the GFC supports decision-making and command execution. The GCN is the
 communications network for the GWS and network connection to the Missile Defense System. The GNI serves as a common secure platform improving real-time cyber
 integration and the ability to detect and respond to cyber events. The IDTs are located at FGA (2); Vandenberg Space Force Base, California (VSFB) (2); Eareckson Air
 Station, Alaska (1); and Fort Drum, New York (1). The IDTs provide secure communications from the GFC to the in-flight interceptors. The GSS consists of the Launch

