$$, $$79549c4fb446fab0d8676d99231c236c165320ab36eb8f1722967f7c4527a897$$, $${"A": "8b10937a5e7e07701e7ee2436c55d9008a82c5f058894024af89612f96257df1", "C": "d4fdf923ba776b98bda680220afe7660b2fb7f78e25f4cb026ad0b29031d9620", "D": "4593981713f9d3f8f887f741e2a00045400e810c86b3e6ec565d3fc2bf1deb43"}$$::jsonb, $$Budget J-Books/FY27/Remaining/RDTE_Vol2_MDA_RDTE_PB27_Justification_Book.pdf$$, 601, $$2026-05-10T04:04:21.937511+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0603913C$$, 2027, $$Since 1986, the United States (U.S.) and the State of Israel have cooperated on the Missile Defense System to defend against short-range rockets, cruise missiles, and
short and medium-range ballistic missiles. This program element supports the State of Israel per international agreements. The Missile Defense Agency, in coordination
with the Israeli Missile Defense Organization, develops and produces two major weapon systems, conducts tests, and exercises interoperability between the U.S. Missile
Defense System and the Israeli Missile Defense Architecture. These major weapon systems include:

 - Arrow Weapon System (MD26).
 - Short-Range Ballistic Missile Defense / David's Sling Weapon System (MD34).

 The U.S. and State of Israel entered into a Memorandum of Understanding in September 2016, in which "Such funding, should over a ten-year period beginning in fiscal
 year (FY) 2019 and ending in FY 2028, be provided at a level of $500 million per year." (U.S. contributions only). These funds will be distributed between the Israeli
 Programs in Research, Development, Test & Evaluation and Procurement Funds.
Advanced Component Development & Prototypes (ACD&P)$$, $$Israeli SRBMD, also known as the DSWS, is designed to counter short range rockets, air breathing threats, medium caliber rockets, and theater ballistic missiles, and is
integrated into the Israeli Missile Defense Architecture. The DSWS includes the Stunner Interceptor (Electro-Optical variant), a Missile Firing Unit, a Multi-Mission Radar
- Next Generation (MMR-NG), a Launch Site Controller, a Ground Data Link (GDL), and the Golden Almond Battle Management Center (GA BMC). The DSWS can be
deployed in a variety of configurations to support the intended mission.

 The DSWS Block 3 capability expands the range and threat versatility of the system by adding the All Weather Stunner Interceptor, improving the MMR-NG, upgrades to
 GDL and increasing the capacity of the GA BMC.

 The U.S. and State of Israel entered into a Memorandum of Understanding on September 2016, in which "Such funding, should over a ten year period beginning in FY
 2019 and ending in FY 2028, be provided at a level of $500 million per year." (U.S. contributions only). These funds will be distributed between the Israeli Programs in
 Research Development Test & Evaluation and Procurement Funds.

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                            FY 2025           FY 2026     FY 2027
Title: SRBMD Program                                                                                                                         127.000           127.000     127.000
                                                                                                                               Articles:          -                 -           -
Description: The DSWS continues system development, testing, and integration of spiral software development for Block 3. Block
3 will provide robust defense capability and add significant detection capability to the Israeli Air Defense Architecture. To ensure
earliest delivery of capability to the Israeli Warfighter, Block 3 is split into three spirals:
- Block 3.0 delivers software updates to the GA BMC made due to warfighter requests.
- Block 3.15 delivers the new All-weather Stunner, improved MMR-NG, improved GDL, improved GA BMC capability and
technology refresh, and expanded threat capability.

                                                                                                                                System (DSWS))

B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions, Article Quantities in Each)                                                       FY 2025       FY 2026        FY 2027
- Block 3.2 delivers refined algorithms for additional threat capability and mission flexibility.

FY 2026 Plans:
- Continue Block 3.15 Development (Systems Requirements Review and Preliminary Design Review).
- Initiate Initial Lot Production of All-weather Stunner.
- Conduct Block 3.2 System Requirements Review.
FY 2027 Plans:
- Conduct Block 3.2 System Requirements Review.
- Initiate Block 4.0 concept definition.
- Continue Initial Lot Production of All-weather Stunner.
- Continue Full Rate Electro-Optical Stunner production.
FY 2026 to FY 2027 Increase/Decrease Statement:
N/A
                                                                                     Accomplishments/Planned Programs Subtotals           127.000     127.000         127.000$$, $$$$, $$The MDA- U.S. Israeli Cooperative Program Office jointly manages the DSWS Program with Israeli Missile Defense Organization (IMDO) to ensure that all systems
are delivered with quality, on time, on budget, and meet the needs of the warfighter. The program funding is equitably funded between the U.S. and Israel with Israel
providing matching contributions. However, a portion of the Israeli cost share comes from non-financial contributions such as previously completed work prior to joint
program initiation. Contracts are awarded by IMDO or MDA, dependent on what is most advantageous to the Joint Governments. In regard to DSWS, IMDO contracts on
behalf of U.S. government with Rafael. Rafael subcontracts with Israeli and U.S. companies.

