A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
Since 1986, the United States (U.S.) and the State of Israel have cooperated on the Missile Defense System to defend against short-range rockets, cruise missiles, and
short and medium-range ballistic missiles. This program element supports the State of Israel per international agreements. The Missile Defense Agency, in coordination
with the Israeli Missile Defense Organization, develops and produces two major weapon systems, conducts tests, and exercises interoperability between the U.S. Missile
Defense System and the Israeli Missile Defense Architecture. These major weapon systems include:

 - Arrow Weapon System (MD26).
 - Short-Range Ballistic Missile Defense / David's Sling Weapon System (MD34).

 The U.S. and State of Israel entered into a Memorandum of Understanding in September 2016, in which "Such funding, should over a ten-year period beginning in fiscal
 year (FY) 2019 and ending in FY 2028, be provided at a level of $500 million per year." (U.S. contributions only). These funds will be distributed between the Israeli
 Programs in Research, Development, Test & Evaluation and Procurement Funds.




